 Nevertheless, I doubled-down on the meager investment I had made, using the platform to think about teaching issues and comment on my military service as I continued my civilian career as a high school teacher and college instructor.</p>\n<p>Some of the posts take on a <a href='http://my-public-affairs.blogspot.com/2014/12/doesnt-it-just-make-sense.html' title='' rel=''>esoteric bent</a>, in line with an induction in the hallowed halls of post-modern, deconstructionist delve into the espitemological foundations of communication and organization that is a doctoral program</p>\n<p><a href='http://my-public-affairs.blogspot.com/search/label/Satire' title='' rel=''>Satire made its debut in 2014</a> following a rejection from the Duffel Blog. They will rue the day. Maybe they had read some of the <a href='http://my-public-affairs.blogspot.com/search/label/Humor' title='' rel=''>humor posts</a> to precede to more brazen satire and were less than impressed</p>\n<p>Perhaps less out of line with my original core competency is the full-throated <a href='http://my-public-affairs.blogspot.com/search/label/All%20Volunteer%20Force' title='' rel=''>defense I wage of the All-Volunteer Force</a>. Call it mission creep</p>\n<p>In all, it’s an eclectic collection of musings whose common theme is me. I teach. I serve in the military. And I try to be funny. My Public Affairs is my attempt to inject some humor and some reflection on teaching and service into a stodgy, stuffy, and too-often unreflective institution. So yes, perhaps above all it is irreverent and a bit contrarian.</p>\n<p>And it’s all out there, on the <em>public</em> World Wide Web</p>\n<p>The photos were not secret, I assured the uneasy captain.</p>\n        <figure>\n          <div>\n            <img src='https://d262ilb51hltx0.cloudfront.net/max/800/1*WIkQOujpAeyE56qSlQpyzw.jpeg' class='post-image'/>\n          </div>\n          <figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption>\n        </figure>\n\n<p>Nothing we do is secret in Army public affairs. If you ask us to take some pictures, they’ll be released. Made public. If you don’t want them public, keep us away.</p>\n<p>Lucky for you and for me, the Greatest Army in the World has no shortage of material just waiting for a good blog post to be written.</p>	2015-07-14 19:46:32.533982	2015-07-14 19:46:32.533982	<p>During a routine clean-up in the Combined Joint Operations Center at Kandahar Airfield, I tossed away a few compact discs.</p>\n<p>A captain behind me had a minor malfunction.</p>\n<p>“What’s on those discs?,” he asked, incredulously concerned that I would throw away a CD so cavalierly.</p>
