t, and over 2800 coalition troops died in battle. The Taliban insurgency rages on. Still, Afghanistan remains a failed state in seemingly perpetual civil war.</p>\n<p>Was it worth it?</p>\n<p>Debating that proposition are four distinguished academics.</p>\n<p>Prof. Amos Guiora teaches law at the University of Utah S. J. Quinney College of Law and is the Co-Director at the Center for Global Justice. He is widely cited as an expert on national security, counterterrorism, and the limits of military power. He served for 19 years in the Israel Defense Forces as Lieutenant Colonel (retired), and held a number of senior command positions, including Commander of the IDF School of Military Law and Legal Advisor to the Gaza Strip.</p>\n<p>Maj. Matt Cavanaugh is an instructor at the United States Military Academy at West Point in the Defense and Security Studies. He served in combat during Operation Iraqi Freedom. He is a term member at the Council on Foreign Relations, and editor at WarCouncil.org, a site dedicated to the study of the use of force.</p>\n<p>Maj. (Ret.) Roger Perkins leads the growing Veterans Support Center which represents over 1000 veterans on campus. His extensive carreer as an Army intelligence officer includes a tour as Assistant Chief of Staff for Intelligence at the Army Special Forces Command. He holds a master’s degree in International Relations and Strategic Studies from Boston University and is a graduate of the US Army Command and General Staff College.</p>\n<p>Rich Stowell is a doctoral candidate in communication and a soldier in the Utah National Guard. He recently returned home from a tour in Afghanistan. He has studied and written on the prospects for democracy in in that country, as well as the intersection of the political and the military in counterinsurgency operations.</p>\n<p>Those in favor of the proposition can argue that, on balance, the West has tamped down a swelling of jihadist terrorism in Afghanistan, that al Qaeda does not pose the threat it did 15 years ago, and that there is hope for a democratic American ally in the the region.</p>\n<p>The other side can point out that Afghanistan is still a failed state, as fragile as ever, and that a very expensive and deadly war has merely postponed the resurgence of radical, violent parties there.</p>\n<p>Winners will not be on the panel, though, but rather in the audience— the attentive students who are the next generation of voters, policy amkers, communicators, soldiers, lawyers, and peace activists.</p>	2015-07-14 19:46:25.941488	2015-07-14 19:46:25.941488	        <figure>\n          <div>\n            <img src='https://medium2.global.ssl.fastly.net/max/1200/1*TAHWqzOLxfOyo9_WAoFzsg.jpeg' class='post-image'/>\n          </div>\n          <figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption>\n        </figure>\n\n<p>Sophomores in college were in the third grade when the U.S. launched its war in Afghanistan.</p>
