r improperly employed, insufficient to potential demands, in transit, exhausted, or distracted, they aren’t as useful. When the battlefield is misunderstood by commanders, they are less likley to see opportunities.</p>\n<p>A rule of thumb offered by the professor— you should be able to determine the purpose of a location within five minutes.</p>\n<p>While the time constraint is arbitrary, the idea is sound. Very soon after taking an initial assessment of a battlespace, a knowledgable observer, perhaps an incoming commander, should be able to know what his options are in terms of the job to be done. His resources should be where he’d expect them to be, ready to be used.</p>\n<p><strong>Order Provides Focus</strong></p>\n<p>An orderly workspace is one that maps out the job. But a battlefield can’t really be considered a workspace, can it? Okay, then let’s just consider the space that military personnel control— the post-battle space or the forward operating base and surrounding security zones.</p>\n<p>Once these are established and secured, tasks become much more manageable. Maneuver units are given areas of operation and develop highly localized expertise. Their jobs become clear. If not, then the suite of actions is presented to them in a way that is easy to interpret.</p>\n<p>Of course, disorder produces distraction, so that when chaotic situations erupt, resources go to those events and cause leaders to become reactive instead of proactive.</p>\n<p><strong>Order Reduces the Chances of Injury</strong></p>\n<p>And death. In a military context, order keeps Soldiers alive. In a combat situation, knowing where troops are, where the enemy is, and how much firepower is available reduces the chance that something goes wrong. Of course in battle, things always go wrong, but a well-ordered space is one in which back ups are available.</p>\n<p>Quick reaction forces are like power tools whose batteries are fully charged. Medical personnel are the safety shut off switch for a 