e that is all selfish. Me, me, me!</em></p>\n<p>Right?</p>\n<p>Wrong.</p>\n<p>I take this newfound knowledge and perspective and pass it onto the dozens of students I interact with through my counseling; I pass it onto the colleagues I meet with and present to at conferences; I pass it onto my fellow graduate students; I pass it onto my family; I pass it onto my two-year-old daughter…</p>\n<p>Learning and research should be selfish because in the end, they never remain selfish.</p>\n        <figure>\n          <div>\n            <img src='https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*lsZ38Q6DjA-EXoCkcwRP0A.jpeg' class='post-image'/>\n          </div>\n          <figcaption class="imageCaption">Doug Robichaud</figcaption>\n        </figure>\n\n<h3>Knowledge can’t be contained. It oozes out of even the most closed minds.</h3>\n<p></p>\n<p>The real problem is not the sharing of information; the real problem is restricting the acquisition of information based on political or economic interests.</p>\n<p>We like to think that when the government funds research it is non-biased and for the good of the people, but when private industry funds it, it is to fuel the greedy capitalist machine.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, government backstage is filled with people who are generalists — enterprising generalists — who know how to move a crowd, garner support and move money around, but not much about any one thing, in particular. We somehow grant them the authority to make laws about topics about which they have very little, if any, knowledge. Hence, we get requests for keeping it simple, proving the validity of your research topic in as few words as possible, speaking in layman’s terms and doing only that which is practical, relevant, and yes, lucrative.</p>\n<p>In this case, specifically, we see an attack on the “soft” sciences, as people call them. After all, social science isn’t real science, is it? Even if our congressmen are requesting non-technical explanations of our work, our science isn’t really “technical” science, is it? And if it’s not technical, as in dealing with the manufacturing of drugs, weapons and maybe a new spaceship, then what good could it possibly serve?</p>\n<p>I’ll leave you with a statement from the National Science Foundation, which I think sums up the answer quite nicely:</p>\n<>We live in extraordinary times, benefiting from unprecedented discovery and innovation. The complexities of national needs escalate with the pace of globalization and communication. As our population expands and becomes more diverse, our quality of life increasingly depends on understanding human factors that can better sustain our environment, prevent illness, maintain a robust economy, curtail conflict and advance democracy. Supporting the best and brightest scientific minds in the social, behavioral and economic sciences is imperative to these goals, enabling the nation and our fellow citizens to address the grand challenges facing our society.</>\n<p><a href='http://www.nsf.gov/about/congress/reports/sbe_research.pdf' title='' rel='nofollow'>http://www.nsf.gov/about/congress/reports/sbe_research.pdf</a></p>	2015-08-04 17:00:43.194342	2015-08-06 15:00:52.891911	<p></p>\n        <figure>\n          <div>\n            <img src='https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*Q4Ims3F1ZM4xYvBGvTnVsg.jpeg' class='post-image'/>\n          </div>\n          <figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption>\n        </figure>\n\n<p>A recent article in <a href='https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/08/03/social-scientists-are-alarmed-new-legislation-nsf-grants' title='' rel=''>Inside Higher Ed</a> reports on proposed legislation by Representative Lamar Smith to insist that the National Science Foundation be more</p>
