98	6	School leaders from across the nation begin “Summer Intensives”	A professional experience of a lifetime	2015-08-03 10:36:01	6bce29600ddb	<h3>School leaders from across the nation begin “Summer Intensives”</h3>\n<p></p>\n<h4><em>A professional experience of a lifetime</em></h4>\n<p></p>\n<p>This month school leaders from districts across the country are embarking on a professional experience of a lifetime. The multi-week “summer intensive” is designed by districts in partnership with NYC Leadership Academy’s (NYCLA) to prepare school leaders for the rigors of the principal or other leadership roles by inserting them into simulated situations commonly experienced on the job.</p>\n<p>From angry parent meetings, to teacher evaluations, to curriculum and professional development planning, to school board meetings and more, the summer intensive develops the leadership skills and reflective stances new principals need to build capacity and improve student outcomes.</p>\n<>“If you can’t get through summer intensive then you shouldn’t be a principal,” says Danika Rux, a NYC APP graduate and current Field Support Liaison at the New York City Department of Education.</>\n<p>“That experience will tell you whether or not you have what it takes to get through the rest of the program. That intensity is what it takes to turn a school around,” Rux said.</p>\n<p>In a school with 98 percent of students receiving free or reduced-price lunch, Principal Rux led her school from an “F” on the NYC Department of Education’s Progress Report to an “A” in four years, proving that low-income doesn’t have to mean low-performing.</p>\n<p>For 13 years, NYCLA’s <a href='http://www.nycleadershipacademy.org/programs-and-services/aspiring-leaders-programs/aspiring-principals-program/index' title='' rel=''>Aspiring Principals Program (APP)</a> has prepared, supported and graduated more than 500 aspiring New York City public school leaders, who went on to lead high-need schools or to take on leadership positions supporting these schools. The APP program is an important part of a bigger portfolio of NYCLA’s leadership development programs and services, which have expanded to 26 states and several countries</p>\n<p>This summer, <a href='http://www.nycleadershipacademy.org/programs-and-services/aspiring-leaders-programs/aspiring-principals-program/index' title='' rel=''>aspiring principals and leaders</a> from Cleveland, New York City, and a national cohort from a group of parochial schools funded by the Commonweal Foundation are taught by some of the most highly experienced facilitators in the field. These new school leaders are put through the paces of typical school days, while honing a vision and plan that will set them up for success as new leaders</p>\n<p>“The reason the APP summer intensive is so important for today’s school leader is that it gives real experience in a safe environment. You get to make mistakes and have someone provide feedback in real time. And you practice the skills needed for situational problem solving,” Rux said. “When you go through traditional university preparation programs, for example, you get content, but not the on-the-job training that medical doctors and other high-stakes professions receive.”</p>\n<p><a href='http://clevelandmetroschools.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=409&ModuleInstanceID=1887&ViewID=047E6BE3-6D87-4130-8424-D8E4E9ED6C2A&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=8739&PageID=1382' title='' rel=''>Speaking to participants in Cleveland Metropolitan School District’s (CMSD) Aspiring Principals Academy, </a>CEO Eric Gordon made it clear that expectations run high in a school district that believes school reform begins with building principals</p>\n<>“You have got to be great for my kids.” — <a href='http://clevelandmetroschools.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=409&ModuleInstanceID=1887&ViewID=047E6BE3-6D87-4130-8424-D8E4E9ED6C2A&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=8739&PageID=1382' title='' rel=''>Cleveland Metropolitan School District’s Aspiring Principals Academy, </a>CEO Eric Gordo</>\n<p>Gordon asked leaders to be “individually and collectively courageous.” He said the district aims to attract and develop principals who take risks but are not divisive mavericks who quickly flame out.</p>\n<p>CMSD received 184 applications for its 2015–16 aspiring principals academy and interviewed 65 applicants. Seven women and three men were chosen. The group is diverse, with three black members and two who are of Latino background.</p>\n<p>“We are very, very proud of this program and its success rate,” Gordon said.</p>\n<p>Following the summer intensive, participants will begin phase three of the APP program — a multi-month residency. Like a medical residency, the APP residency provides aspiring leaders with authentic opportunities to practice school leadership with the support of trained mentor principals and APP coaches.</p>\n<p>It is the experiential learning of a well-designed residency that enables an aspiring school leader to be more fully prepared for the vitally important and complex job of a school leader.</p>\n<p>Before assuming a leadership position in which they are responsible for a school, APP participants complete a planning phase tailored to their unique school community. The process ensures a strong start and a continued connection to their fellow APP cohort to share ideas and reflect on the challenges and opportunities of their profession. That’s why this kind of experiential, standards based learning is an unmatched professional opportunity of a lifetime.</p>\n<p>A principal’s first day on the job is not the time to negotiate competing priorities and respond to crises du jour while evaluating and guiding teaching practices.</p>\n<p>The summer intensive and the other APP components immerse aspiring principals in the daily rhythms of a school day in all of its non-stop action, high-energy, complicated, struggles and glory.</p>\n<>Through these intensive and deliberate experiences, leaders become adept at dealing with the challenges at hand and remain deeply focus on student learning.</>\n<p>Much is at stake. As NYCLA CEO Irma Zardoya states: “Schools are one of the most important places where we can change the tide of race, gender, ethnic and class inequities to build a country that truly embraces each human being having equal and inalienable rights.” That is NYCLA’s imperative and why programs like this one are crucial.</p>\n<p><em>For more information about programs for aspiring principals and leaders go to www.nycleadershipacademy.org</em></p>	2015-07-24 01:01:03.899238	2015-08-03 11:01:20.729151	<h3>School leaders from across the nation begin “Summer Intensives”</h3>\n<p></p>\n<h4><em>A professional experience of a lifetime</em></h4>
99	6	3 Reasons Why Andy Weir’s The Martian Matters	Andy Weir’s bestselling science fiction novel The Martian reminded me of the science fiction from the mid-twentieth century I read as a…	2015-07-23 14:12:18	19508a6f290f	<p></p>\n<p>Andy <a href='https://twitter.com/andyweirauthor' title='' rel=''>Weir</a>’s bestselling science fiction novel <a href='http://andyweirauthor.com/books/the-martian-hc' title='' rel=''><em>The Martian</em></a> reminded me of the science fiction from the mid-twentieth century I read as a child. Even though authors like Bradbury and Asimov were writing about worlds that would exist during my lifetime, the allure of the possible was intoxicating. Earlier science fiction writers like Verne and Wells established a genre that pushed not only the limits of our technology but also what it meant to be truly “human”</p>\n<p>As a person that reads often, I have always adored these classic works of science fiction but have noticed that my own two sons, 13 and 9, have little interest in or access to contemporary science fiction. Sure, the genre hasn’t died but it has drastically morphed into a very formulaic view that the “future” is wrought with doom and gloom.</p>\n<p>This is what allows Weir’s <em>The Martian </em>to be so compelling. While the novel is centered on the conflict of survival, it revives the science fiction genre in 3 ways</p>\n<p><strong>It’s not dystopian.</strong></p>\n<p>Contemporary science fiction is mired in the downward spiral of human civilization. Science either is the cause of or the savior for humanity’s fate. In either case the options are depressing instead of inspiring. Hence the rise of dystopian science fiction, and our seemingly unquenchable thirst that forecast our inevitable destruction. I understand the purpose, the author’s intent, is to prognosticate a warning about humanity’s path. A “it’s not too late” alarm for our current generation, but the overwhelming saturation of these types of work convey a consensus rather than a warning. The outcome is destined instead of a choice.</p>\n<p>Weir’s novel portrays a future where space exploration, while still not a unified human endeavor and still impacted by geo-political concerns, is fundamentally woven into the fabric of our world. It’s not the result of a dying Earth (i.e. Interstellar) or the cause of Earth’s destruction. Space exploration is a natural extension of our human spirit: to go places where no one has ever been before. Weir accurately shows the reader a future world that continues to honor this basic human drive while also showing the reader a world functioning and not disintegrating.</p>\n<p><strong>Humanity can work together.</strong></p>\n<p>Another interesting trend in contemporary dystopian fiction is that the fate of humanity rests with the power of 1. Pick your favorite book series and more than likely the main character is charged with the task of rescuing all of us. The archetype is an ancient one, but the proliferation of this trope spotlights a modern movement, the power of the individual, or more accurately, the power of acting as a unique individual. Whether it’s <em>Hunger Games, Ender’s Game, </em>or <em>Divergent</em>, the whole of humanity has become lock step with some powerful overlord, but there is the chosen one that must save the rest of us</p>\n<p>While Weir’s novel does focus on the one character and his struggles, the story illustrates the best of humanity: our collective ability to work together to solve the unsolvable. Instead of using his novel to scare humanity into action, Weir creates a situation where humanity’s strengths are used to save each of us. Astronaut Mark Watney is our modern day representation of John Donne’s “No Man is an Island”. We all share a responsibility for each other.</p>\n<p><strong>Individuals are creators and are not subordinate to our technology.</strong></p>\n<p>A characteristic of our contemporary science fiction is the fact that we fear humanity will become servant to its creation, technology. While that argument is extremely valid and to a very real degree, we already are, in dystopian fiction our relationship with technology and science always leads us astray. It’s the fast track to our demise.</p>\n<p>There is a movement, that is gaining momentum, which Weir adeptly taps into, and it’s “the individual as maker”. Certainly our world has become populated with consumers. But the pendulum is swinging away from passive consumerism. Our kids want to create. Whether it’s structured “maker-spaces” in schools, playing <em>Minecraft </em>at home, or the resurgence of Lego, our next generation seems to be seeded in seeking satisfaction from ‘crafting’(as the gamers call it)</p>\n<p>Weir’s Watney is our next generation’s “everyman”. Again and again Watney reminds us he is just a botanist and he barely knows any chemistry, but he continually uses his skills, resources, and ingenuity to overcome insurmountable problems. While the novel is primarily his story, we see “everymen” working on Earth, using his/her own skills, resources, and ingenuity to overcome insurmountable problems. Imagine the potential of humanity if each of us embraced our primal “maker” selves within the context of our modern world.</p>\n<p>The two movements are not in conflict with each other. Making and science go hand-in-hand. It’s when the ‘making’ becomes the exclusive ability of the few that humanity disintegrates. Weir’s novel shows us a not-to-distant-future that rectifies these two ends.</p>	2015-07-24 17:01:10.389434	2015-07-24 17:01:10.389434	<p></p>\n<p>Andy <a href='https://twitter.com/andyweirauthor' title='' rel=''>Weir</a>’s bestselling science fiction novel <a href='http://andyweirauthor.com/books/the-martian-hc' title='' rel=''><em>The Martian</em></a> reminded me of the science fiction from the mid-twentieth century I read as a child. Even though authors like Bradbury and Asimov were writing about worlds that would exist during my lifetime, the allure of the possible was intoxicating. Earlier science fiction writers like Verne and</p>
97	7	The Number Line: A Powerful and Versatile Model	Aha! Moment	2015-07-23 21:02:44	344580a8cbbe	<h4>Aha! Moment</h4>\n<p></p>\n<p>The number line is a powerful model that helps students develop flexibility in their thinking. Throughout the <em>Eureka Math</em> curriculum the number line is used to enable students to develop strong number sense and to recognize relationships among numbers. Early elementary students develop their thinking using manipulatives and the number path, which leads them to ultimately understand how to use the number line. The simplicity of the number line allows math students of all levels to develop an understanding of the relative magnitude and position of numbers. It’s also a strong aid in helping students work towards proficiency in visualizing operations. In this blog, I will illustrate how this model develops from Grade PK to Grade 6</p>\n<h4>Pre-K</h4>\n<p>In Grade PK, students learn to count the “math way” from 1 to 5, starting at their left pinky and moving towards their left thumb, which prepares them to count from 6 to 10 beginning with the right thumb and continuing to the right pinky.</p>\n\n<p>This prepares them for understanding the number path and the number line. In these early elementary years, students learn that numbers on the number line increase from left to right. The part of the number line to the left of zero isn’t addressed until much later.</p>\n<p>Students also discover the pattern of <em>1 more</em> through the development of number stairs for quantities of 1 to 5, realizing that as they move one step to the right, they are increasing the value by 1 more than they started</p>\n\n<h4>Grade K</h4>\n<p>In Grade K, students continue this idea that each successive number refers to a quantity that is one more than the previous number. They also recognize that the number before any given number is one less than that number, continuing the learning from PK where students broke down a tower of 5, removing one cube at a time while counting backwards. This understanding allows students to develop the idea of counting on rather than counting all, which begins in Grade K and develops further in Grade 1. Multiple opportunities are provided for students to develop their understanding of numbers and build intuitive strategies for solving addition and subtraction problems using the Rekenrek. This also aids in setting the foundation for students to understand the number line.</p>\n\n<h4>Grade 1</h4>\n<p>In Grade 1, students use the number path to solve various problems. In the problem below, students solve for the unknown part:</p>\n<>5 + ___ = 8</>\n<p>Students may start at 5, hop to 8 and determine there are 3 hops so the missing value is 3. After first determining the unknown to have a value of 3, students can then use the number path again to solve a related subtraction sentence, 8–5 = _____ and determine the unknown is 3.</p>\n\n<h4>Grade 2</h4>\n<p>The number line is first explicitly addressed in Grade 2 and is supported by the 20-bead Rekenrek. Students can see numbers to 10 as a number line and further develop their number sense. They begin working with the clock as a circular number line where the clock is made from a ribbon and marked at 12 points.</p>\n\n\n<p>Students count backward and forward in intervals of five and relate the place on the ribbon to time. In Grade 2, students also relate addition and subtraction to length and begin to use the ruler as a number line where they measure lengths of line segments, find the sum of both line segments and compare the lengths (see image below to the left).</p>\n<p>Towards the end of Grade 2, students draw and label a bar graph to represent data. They notice how the numbers on the graph help record data and also provide a tool that allows for a more efficient way of creating the graph, rather than counting each box to record the value in each category. Students also recognize the scale helps with more precise comparisons and relate the scale on the graph to the number line.</p>\n\n<h4>Grade 3</h4>\n<p>In Grade 3, students have many opportunities to use the number line to aid in strengthening their understanding of various math concepts.<strong> </strong>They build upon their knowledge in Grade 2 and use the number line in Eureka lessons to tell time to the nearest minute. They count by fives and ones and solve word problems involving time intervals within 1 hour by counting backward and forward. The number line is used as a tool to help add and subtract to solve word problems involving time intervals within 1 hour</p>\n\n<p>In addition, students use the number line to see fractions as numbers and begin using the interval from 0 to 1, where 1 represents the whole. They partition, place, count, and compare fractions. They also notice equivalent fractions are placed at the exact same point and recognize that whole numbers can be written as fractions.</p>\n\n<h4>Grade 4</h4>\n<p>In Grade 4, students extend their learning in Grade 3 with unit fractions to explore fraction equivalence and extend this understanding to mixed numbers. A variety of models are used to aid in comparing fractions and mixed numbers as well as representing them. Benchmark fractions, such as 1/2, 1/3 and 1/4, are crucial as students work to generalize and make sense of the size of relative fractions and mixed numbers.</p>\n\n<p>In the problem shown below asks a student to: <em>Use a number line, multiplication, and division to decompose and compose fractions. </em>Students first partition a number line into thirds and then decompose 1 third into 4 equal parts. Next, they write a number sentence using multiplication to show a fraction equivalent to 1 third on the number line (4/12)</p>\n\n<p>Students also write the equivalence as a number sentence using division. Students verbalize that four copies of 1 twelfth is equal to 1 third and it’s possible to compose smaller units to make a larger unit.</p>\n<p>In Grade 4, students also use the number line to compare fractions.</p>\n\n<h4>Grade 5</h4>\n<p>In Grade 5 students build upon their work in Grade 4 to add fractions to and subtract fractions from whole numbers and mixed numbers.</p>\n\n<p>Another way students use the number line is to assist in rounding decimals. In the example below, students decompose to round 9.975 to the nearest one, ten, tenth and hundredth.</p>\n\n<p>In the final module in Grade 5, students relate the number line to the coordinate plane and graph coordinates in quadrant 1.</p>\n\n<h4>Grade 6</h4>\n<p>In Grade 6, students extend their knowledge of the number line and the work done in <em>A Story of Units</em> to include the left side of zero: the negative numbers. Through strengthening their understanding of negative numbers, students build upon their work in Grade 5 in the first quadrant and further relate the number line to the coordinate plane to graph in all four quadrants</p>\n\n\n<p>The number line model is one that appears frequently throughout the Eureka curriculum and this blog certainly does not illustrate every application of this model from Grade PK to Grade 6. Although the progression of the number line was only highlighted until Grade 6, the first year of <em>A Story of Ratios</em>, this model makes many appearances throughout the rest of <em>A Story of Ratios</em> and <em>A Story of Functions</em>. I challenge you to find examples of how this model is used throughout Grades 7 to 12</p>\n<p><em>This post is authored by <a href='https://www.facebook.com/pages/Dawn-Pensack-Eureka-Math-Grades-5-6/1628157847414042?fref=ts' title='' rel=''>Dawn Pensack</a>, a </em><a href='https://www.facebook.com/eurekamathofficial' title='' rel=''>Eureka Math</a><em> writer for </em><a href='https://www.facebook.com/pages/Eureka-Math-Grade-6/921873154531571?ref=hl' title='' rel=''>A Story of Ratios</a> (Grades 6–8)</p>	2015-07-23 23:00:20.33026	2015-09-24 01:00:31.19149	<h4>Aha! Moment</h4>\n<p></p>\n<p>The number line is a p