nd sisters and parents and grandparents how to do math. And they have an attitude that they want to learn more.</p>\n<p><strong>Why aren’t more schools using it?</strong></p>\n<p>I’m sure there is at least one teacher in every school [in Mercer County] using it, probably about a third of elementary teachers overall in Mercer. But a lot of teachers are a little leery of using what the county hasn’t trained them to use. The county endorses the use of <em>Eureka Math</em> now, but we still use <em>Everyday Math </em>as a curriculum. <em>Eureka Math</em> is not something you can do a little of. It needs to start at the beginning and it works better if all teachers in your school are using it. Once I get teachers to use it, they love it</p>\n<p><strong>What turned the tide?</strong></p>\n<p>Their STAR [interim test] scores. We had huge jumps on the STAR Renaissance test this year in math, not in English. I’m sure it was because of <em>Eureka Math</em>. They could see how much progress their kids were making. At that point, they didn’t care what it was called</p>	2015-08-20 17:00:28.705148	2015-08-24 11:00:32.981264	<h4><strong>Erika Wimmer — </strong><em>Teacher, Spanishburg Elementary School</em></h4>\n<p></p>\n<p><em>Erika Wimmer is a teacher at Spanishburg Elementary School in Mercer County, WV, a rural district in the southern part of the state. She taught a 4th/5th grade split class this past year, but has taught most of the elementary</em></p>
101	6	Want to Work on a Startup? Don’t Take College Loans	Why wouldn’t you take a job that gives you real motivation, flow, and productivity? Student debt would be one reason.	2015-07-26 01:34:53	694773c926dc	<>Photo Credit: <a href='http://startupstockphotos.com/' title='' rel=''>Startup Stock Photos</a></>\n<p>Joining a startup team is an amazing, wild, incredibly worthwhile experience. You get to work on a growing project and see real, tangible products of your work on an innovative, risk-taking team, and you are forced to grow your skills daily in order to succeed. It’s an experience I would encourage almost any young person to take if the opportunity presents itself.</p>\n<p>It can also be relatively costly.</p>\n<p>If you’re lucky and get in early enough, you’ll probably get equity, but the equity isn’t really worth much unless there’s an exit. You’ll get a salary, but it will probably be much lower than taking a job at Megafaceless Corp, LLC. in Manhattan, or some government bureaucracy in DC. And there’s a good chance that you will be living in a place like the Bay Area, Austin, or Boston, all of which have crazy expensive costs of living.</p>\n<p>That isn’t to say that it doesn’t pay off in satisfaction, long-term options, or even financial rewards, depending on the way you take that experience.It’s simply to say that taking a job at a startup as a young person when there are other options in more traditional roles at more traditional companies is something that can be <em>relatively </em>costly. Lots of entrepreneurial young people would kill for the opportunity to be part of a growing, innovative team doing work that is the direct consequence of their day-to-day actions. When you work at a large organization, it’s a lot harder to see the consequences of your hard work</p>\n<p>In <em>Office Space</em>, Peter Gibbons, the apathetic protagonist caught in an ennui-inspiring job for the drab Initech corporation notes this exact sentiment</p>\n<><em>Peter Gibbons: The thing is, Bob, it’s not that I’m lazy, it’s that I just don’t care.\nBob Porter: Don’t… don’t care?\nPeter Gibbons: It’s a problem of motivation, all right? Now if I work my ass off and Initech ships a few extra units, I don’t see another dime, so where’s the motivation?</em></>\n<p>To see the real consequences of shipping a few more units, to stay up at night to make sure you can compile all your code because you want to launch a new site on the next day, to travel across the country to make a sale that can bring thousands in for the company, and to see all this happening because you are working hard is something that brings motivation itself.</p>\n<p>So why <em>wouldn’t</em> you take a job that allows you that kind of motivation, flow, and productivity</p>\n<p>Student debt would be one reason.</p>\n<p>Young people are presented statistics and testimonials while growing up, getting ready to apply to college, and going through college about how a college degree is worth X payoff and taking out loans makes sense to get that degree to achieve X payoff.</p>\n<p>Making that extra chunk of money associated with a degree (which is a dubious statement based on broad generalizations about opportunity costs, but that can be ignored for now) may be a great motivation to take out loans if all you are concerned about is making more money, but if you are concerned about more than just making money and instead care about the <a href='https://medium.com/synapse/it-s-not-about-working-for-free-it-s-about-being-free-15b8e03a179e' title='' rel=''>opportunity and freedom</a> to pursue your goals like working on a startup or launching your own venture (something that is itself very costly), then you should think twice before signing off on those student loans</p>\n<p>If you have $45,000 in student loans for a generic degree from a liberal arts college, you might get past the HR lady at a nonprofit or a corporation you are kind of interested in that will pay you $40,000 or $50,000 your first year. If you can’t afford to pursue a startup that will pay you less but will help you come alive as a person, then your student loans haven’t <em>meaningfully</em> opened up options for you. For what you are trying to achieve from your professional life and your education, taking on student debt has actually made your life more difficult and stymied your ability to meet those goals</p>\n<p>To imagine it another way, taking out a loan (n) to buy a large pickup truck may open up plenty of options for moving things around, helping people with their stuff, or launching a lawn care, carpentry, or plumbing business. You could crunch numbers about how all these things can provide a payoff that is n+1, making it financially worthwhile for people to take out loans to get pickup trucks. But this example is patently absurd because we recognize that not everybody is going to need a pickup truck to achieve their goals. Even more, purchasing that pickup truck and being forced to pay off the loan for it shuts out options that would have otherwise been available, like driving long distances economically. If your goal was to go on a road trip, start your own delivery service, or even become an Uber driver in your spare time, the advice that you needed to take out a loan for a pickup truck actually <em>undermines </em>your goals</p>\n<p>The <em>Wall Street Journal </em><a href='http://www.wsj.com/articles/want-to-be-an-entrepreneur-beware-of-student-debt-1432318500' title='' rel=''>recently ran a piece</a> recently noting some empirical observations that back up this claim that student debt makes it harder to launch or get involved in new business ventures</p>\n<><em>In the study, published last year, researchers looked at student debt across the U.S. by ZIP Code and compared it with small-business formation in those areas. Between 2000 and 2010, a one-standard-deviation increase in student debt in a ZIP Code led to an average 25% reduction in the number of very small businesses, those with one to five employees.</em></>\n<p>Even if you aren’t looking to start this business, getting involved in a venture with a low starting salary is something that you can only do if you have the freedom from debt to do so. Isaac Morehouse <a href='http://blog.discoverpraxis.com/debt-can-limit-your-options/' title='' rel=''>puts it well</a></p>\n<><em>the lower your wage requirements, the more flexibility you have early on to explore and test and find work you love. Keep that in mind with each step. Ask whether your present decisions are limiting your future options in a way you might regret.</em></>\n<p>So next time somebody harangues you about how you just need to take out more loans to finish your degree, ask yourself if doing so is going to open the <em>right doors for you</em>. Opening more doors isn’t always a good thing. And it rarely comes without closing others</p>\n<p><em>Zachary Slayback is the Business Development Director for <a href='http://discoverpraxis.com/' title='' rel='nofollow'>Praxis</a>, a ten-month program for entrepreneurial learners. Zachary dropped out of the University of Pennsylvania after seeing firsthand how college fails the most ambitious students. He writes regularly on education, schooling, and philosophy at <a href='http://zakslayback.com/' title='' rel='nofollow'>zakslayback.com</a>.</em></p>\n<p><em>Originally published as </em>“If You Want to Work on a Startup, Avoid College Loans”<em> at <a href='http://zakslayback.com/2015/05/26/if-you-want-to-work-on-a-startup-avoid-college-loans/' title='' rel=''>zakslayback.com</a> on May 27, 2015.</em></p>	2015-07-26 03:00:52.336419	2015-07-26 03:00:52.336419	<h2>Want to Work on a Startup? Don’t Take College Loans</h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>Joining a startup team is an amazing, wild, incredibly worthwhile experience. You get to work on a growing project and see real…</p>
102	6	What The Largest State In The US Can Learn From The Happiest Country In The World	Texas wants 60% of young people to have some sort of degree within 6 years of graduating high school.	2015-07-27 17:00:03	c60c3a1bb410	        <figure>\n          <div>\n            <img src='https://d262ilb51hltx0.cloudfront.net/max/800/1*BFw8IY9JA7Jza5XwP2CEGQ.jpeg' class='post-image'/>\n          </div>\n          <figcaption class="imageCaption">Mt. Titilis, The Swiss Alps, Alex Ellison.</figcaption>\n        </figure>\n\n<p></p>\n<p>Texas wants <a href='http://www.texastribune.org/2015/03/21/more-eighth-graders-get-degree-increase-small/' title='' rel=''>60% of young people</a> to have some sort of degree within 6 years of graduating high school</p>\n<p>In Switzerland, nearly 100% of the population has either a university degree, a trade school degree or professional training.</p>\n<p>I’m pinpointing Switzerland because I’m currently doing research here, but also because the US is quite interested in their “dual” education model and how it could work back home.</p>\n<p>Just two weeks ago, an agreement was signed between the US and Switzerland to bring Vocational and Educational training to the US. Swiss firms in the US will expand apprenticeship programs, using local community colleges to hold the instruction segments and their own firms for the work segments. This. Is. Happening. <a href='http://bern.usembassy.gov/ev-07092015.html' title='' rel=''>Coming to a city near you!</a></p>\n<p>Here’s the problem with the Texas plan and others like it in the US.</p>\n<><strong><em>We are shoving all students through a narrow funnel, into a homogenous learning model that is higher education in the US.</strong></em></>\n<p>Whether a student chooses community college or an elite 4-year college, we call it college. The student is forced to choose a <em>version</em> of college, but college is still the only option</p>\n<p>So what about the kids who cannot stand the thought of sitting in a classroom, getting through more core requirements after they complete compulsory schooling? Well, these kids can tell their families, with head hanging and eyes down to the floor, that they are going to forgo college education (the scenario is even more bleak for children of immigrants, whose parents may have come to the US in large part so their children could obtain higher education). Then, they either work in Bob’s auto shop until they feel like experts and maybe open their own shop, or hope to become the next Mark Zuckerberg…</p>\n<p>There really is no designated path for the kid who knows he wants to start working, who knows exactly where his passions lie and who doesn’t want any distractions.</p>\n<p>There is no job training that combines classroom time with work time to give a student a degree in a specialized field and a career that he can be proud of. <strong>No, we don’t have that in the US, but this is an integral part of Swiss society.</strong></p>\n<p>When the US comes gawking at their smooth-running machine that is dual education, the Swiss couldn’t imagine it any other way. Only about 30% of students choose the university path. The rest choose one of many options for professional training, be it in sales, carpentry, hairdressing or manufacturing. Students who choose this latter path can go on to graduate from “Fachhochschule”, university for the trades, and earn the same respect (if not more) as their peers in university.</p>\n<p>This also means that universities are not all things to all people in Switzerland — they don’t have to be. There’s no reason that turf management or even business, should be housed at a university. <strong>These are career-centric subjects for career-minded students. Students who want to pursue these fields should have a path open to them, not just a college path, that allows them to receive highly specialized, quality training in their fields.</strong></p>\n<p>I would bet that if students in Texas had a similar dual model in which students desiring to enter a trade could study and learn on the job without the same course requirements and expectations as at a college or university, then Texas would exceed its 60% goal. And even better, its young people (from both the university path and the trade path) would feel greater career pride, knowing they are truly experts in their fields, doing work that is really quite special.</p>\n<p><em>Alex Ellison is the Founder and Chief Dunce at <a href='http://duncecp.com/' title='' rel=''>Dunce Labs</a>, where she helps students launch their futures — to college and beyond.</em></p>	2015-07-26 03:00:53.084024	2015-08-03 15:01:20.91919	        <figure>\n          <div>\n            <img src='https://d262ilb51hltx0.cloudfront.net/max/800/1*BFw8IY9JA7Jza5XwP2CEGQ.jpeg' class='post-image'/>\n          </div>\n          <figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption>\n        </figure>\n\n<p>Texas wants <a href='http://www.texastribune.org/2015/03/21/more-eighth-graders-get-degree-increase-small/' title='' rel=''>60% of young people</a> to have some sort of degree within 6 years of graduating high</p>
117	6	Rockaway Avenue	Acknowledging privilege while confronting nuanced inequalities.	2015-08-03 19:17:17	5c6d27cb52d0	<h3>Acknowledging privilege while confronting nuanced inequalities.</h3>\n<p>When people use the word privilege, I’m definitely not the first thing people visualize. I moved to the United States when I was three, and my parents worked tirelessly to ensure that my siblings and I would have the education and opportunities unavailable to them in the Philippines. Personally, when I think of privilege, my mind immediately conjures an image of the quintessential white girl who says stuff like “my life is harder than yours because I have to <em>feel guilty</em> about my parents paying the full cost of my tuition.” I’m not white, and consequently, I’m at a disadvantage to my white counterparts. That’s not up for debate. Yet, since I grew up in middle class suburbia, I had access to many more opportunities to succeed than most</p>\n<p>I still identified with some of the various struggles people of color face. When I was in school, all my classmates saw were the cultural divides between us. The reality of being a minority includes encountering microaggressions: being the punch line of jokes, or being undermined in the classroom or work place on a daily basis. There are additionally other, more concrete difficulties that are associated with being an immigrant, such as trying to provide for a family and save for the future with little to no savings, and even employment discrimination that comes along with having an “ethnic” last name. Sometimes all that bullshit just swirls in your head and hearing a coworker joke about subservient stereotypes of Asian women seems almost as awful as institutionalized discrimination. <strong>So as an Asian American from a working class family, I thought I understood, to some degree, the plight of being black in America.</strong></p>\n<h3>In a predictable turn of events where the students in a classroom teach the instructor, I was wrong.</h3>\n<p></p>\n<p>I volunteered for an organization called <a href='http://www.generationcitizen.org/' title='' rel=''>Generation Citizen</a> last semester, because I had always found myself in teaching positions and am passionate about politics & policy. It was one of those opportunities that brought out the best in me. I wanted to help those who are all too often ignored by traditional modes of political empowerment, partly because I too, had felt powerless and marginalized by existing institutions of power. Just maybe not to the same extent</p>\n<p>The school where I worked was in Ocean Hill, on the cusps of Brownsville, Brooklyn. The building was a short walk from the the Rockaway Avenue subway stop, and each time I emerged from the station I felt immersed in a much different New York than the Village I’d begun to call home. Nestled in a predominately black neighborhood, the school building itself housed four different public and charter schools. On my first day, I was completely lost and disoriented when I tried to find the classroom on my own — despite being in the right building and on the right floor. My fellow co-Democracy Coach and I often felt a little out of place, despite both of our minority backgrounds. Brownsville is actually <a href='http://nymag.com/news/features/brownsville-2014-6/' title='' rel=''>notorious for it’s youth gang violence</a>, and my co-DC and I were responsible for a class of 8th grade boys in the same demographic. Initially, I was intimidated by the middle schoolers; they were proud and rambunctious and determined to present a tough front</p>\n<p>As a student instructor coming from outside their neighborhood, I couldn’t help but feel like the boys saw us as rich kids who wanted to feel good about themselves a couple times a week. Throughout the semester, we discussed local civics and created plans for advocacy. Our class was focused on mitigating gang violence in the local parks, while the class across the hall wanted to advocate against police brutality. Eventually, we felt comfortable with one another to divulge details about our lives. Some of the boys wanted to know what college was like, and others were just thankful that they were assigned two female Democracy Coaches. Halfway through the semester, our concerns with youth gang violence intensified after a territorial brawl broke out after school and one of my students was caught in the fray. Still, even as we drew up plans to address the issues occurring a block away from the school, it still felt foreign and distant to me. After all, each afternoon I’d get back on the train and go back to Manhattan. I might not have been a “rich” college student looking to exploit my students for points on a resume, but I definitely wasn’t one and the same with my students either. It never sunk in that I was constantly walking away from their underserved community and back to my privileged one.</p>\n<p>The day after the NYPD aggressively halted protests in Union Square, I thought it was necessary to discuss Freddie Gray’s tragic death with my class. I remembered when I was in 7th grade and my band teacher let us watch President Obama’s inauguration on his TV. It was technically a digression from our studies, but immensely important.</p>\n        <figure>\n          <div>\n            <img src='https://cdn-images-2.medium.com/max/600/1*srW-_yK39AJ5lMAQpWNEMg.jpeg' class='post-image'/>\n          </div>\n          <figcaption class="imageCaption">Protesters Gather in Union Square in response to Freddie Gray’s death: April 30, 2015</figcaption>\n        </figure>\n\n<p>I showed them the pictures I had taken for the school newspaper, and recounted stories of classmates being arrested and blaring announcements through the night. Some of the students were impressed that I had taken the photos myself, others glanced out the window. Finally, I made a passing remark about helicopters monitoring the lingering crowd’s movements.</p>\n<h4>“<em>Damn</em>, she must live in a nice neighborhood,” one kid glanced at his peer, “They would never check up on here.</h4>\n<p></p>\n<p>I paused. I was in front of the classroom, trying to foster solidarity, but for what? The fact that whirring helicopter blades woke up my roommates? I had been concerned after my classmates had been peacefully arrested and held for a few hours, yet each day these kids had to be concerned about bumping into the wrong people, or rubbing a cop the wrong way. They worried about ending up beaten or dead. I was the one instructing them how to advocate for themselves in an unjust world, all while not fully comprehending the significance of their injustice. The consequences of the racial inequality that impacted my students were radically different than anything I had experienced.</p>\n<p>What does one say when a student calls out their privilege? Do I pretend like I have the same visceral understand of their life experience? Do I qualify the opportunities that my parents and and home community gave me? Do I justify where I live and go to school with the impending student debt that will haunt me for the rest of my adult life?</p>\n<p>Or do I acknowledge my privilege and accept the fact that life has thrown some wicked adversities my way, and I <em>still</em> had a much better chance than others. Despite my own underprivileged status as an woman, immigrant and racial minority, I cannot ignore the blessings automatically granted by my socioeconomic status and familial support. Nor should I become defensive and offended when I’m reminded of those blessings</p>\n<p>It’s difficult to accept privilege I didn’t ask for. To check my privilege feels like I’m copping up to cheating on a test or taking something that isn’t rightfully mine — despite jumping through the hoops of putting in hard work over the years. I felt pangs of guilt when I observed my students desperately trying to make the most out of an education I had taken for granted most of my adolescent life. Feeling guilty and feeling like I deserved to live the life I have was a troubling emotional dichotomy. Yes, I worked hard and ultimately turned things around for the better, but it pains me to wonder what good my students and their contemporaries could have done, if only they had the same resources I had growing up.</p>\n<p>Ultimately, I cannot change what circumstances that I or my students must face. I cannot begin to fully rationalize or pretend to comprehend what those less privileged than I are<em> <a href='http://blacklivesmatter.com/about/' title='' rel=''>trying to call to national attention</a></em>. However, what I can and must do is be completely honest with my students and myself when staring in the face of inequality. Literally and figuratively, it’s not all black and white. Sometimes, people fall in between; they aren’t able to claim all the loveliness of privilege, yet they cannot claim to be completely marginalized. Discourse shouldn’t be a contest to see who has the moral high ground or who has it the worst. Rather, we should attempt to see our differences in a light of integrity. Even when that means checking a privilege we hadn’t previously known we had</p>	2015-08-03 17:01:17.47215	2015-08-06 09:00:38.774352	<h2>Rockaway Avenue</h2>\n<h3>Acknowledging privilege while confronting nuanced inequalities.</h3>\n<p></p>\n<p>When people use the word privilege, I’m definitely not the first thing people…</p>
